{
    "question_text": "<h3>42. Trapping Rain Water</h3><p>Given <code>n</code> non-negative integers representing an elevation map where the width of each bar is <code>1</code>, compute how much water it can trap after raining.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong class=\"example\">Example 1:</strong></p>\n<img src=\"https://assets.leetcode.com/uploads/2018/10/22/rainwatertrap.png\" style=\"width: 412px; height: 161px;\" />\n<pre>\n<strong>Input:</strong> height = [0,1,0,2,1,0,1,3,2,1,2,1]\n<strong>Output:</strong> 6\n<strong>Explanation:</strong> The above elevation map (black section) is represented by array [0,1,0,2,1,0,1,3,2,1,2,1]. In this case, 6 units of rain water (blue section) are being trapped.\n</pre>\n\n<p><strong class=\"example\">Example 2:</strong></p>\n\n<pre>\n<strong>Input:</strong> height = [4,2,0,3,2,5]\n<strong>Output:</strong> 9\n</pre>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Constraints:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li><code>n == height.length</code></li>\n\t<li><code>1 &lt;= n &lt;= 2 * 10<sup>4</sup></code></li>\n\t<li><code>0 &lt;= height[i] &lt;= 10<sup>5</sup></code></li>\n</ul>\n",
    "difficulty": "HARD",
    "marks": 20,
    "input_format": "A single line containing space-separated non-negative integers representing the `height` array.",
    "output_format": "A single integer denoting the units of trapped rain water.",
    "constraints": [
        "n == height.length",
        "1 <= n <= 2 * 10^4",
        "0 <= height[i] <= 10^5"
    ],
    "explanation": "To calculate trapped water at any index `i`, we need the maximum height to its left and the maximum height to its right. The water trapped above index `i` is `min(max_left, max_right) - height[i]`.\nAn optimal O(N) time and O(1) space solution uses Two Pointers. We initialize `left = 0` and `right = len(height) - 1`, tracking `left_max` and `right_max`. We iterate inward. If `height[left] < height[right]`, we know the limiting factor for trapped water is definitely on the left side, as `right_max` will always be >= `height[right]` which is > `height[left]`. So if `height[left] >= left_max`, we update `left_max`, otherwise we add `left_max - height[left]` to our trapped water total, then increment `left`. Conversely, we do the same for the right side if `height[left] >= height[right]`. This elegantly maps the trapping area in a single pass.",
    "answer": "def solve(height):\n    if not height:\n        return 0\n    left, right = 0, len(height) - 1\n    left_max, right_max = 0, 0\n    ans = 0\n    while left < right:\n        if height[left] < height[right]:\n            if height[left] >= left_max:\n                left_max = height[left]\n            else:\n                ans += left_max - height[left]\n            left += 1\n        else:\n            if height[right] >= right_max:\n                right_max = height[right]\n            else:\n                ans += right_max - height[right]\n            right -= 1\n    return ans",
    "boilerplate": {
        "python": "import sys\n\ndef solve(height):\n    # User logic should be written here\n    return 0\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    input_data = sys.stdin.read().split()\n    if input_data:\n        height = list(map(int, input_data))\n        print(solve(height))\n    else:\n        print(0)",
        "cpp": "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint solve(vector<int>& height) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n    return 0;\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int val;\n    vector<int> height;\n    while (cin >> val) {\n        height.push_back(val);\n    }\n    cout << solve(height) << endl;\n    return 0;\n}",
        "java": "import java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static int solve(int[] height) {\n        // User logic should be written here\n        return 0;\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);\n        ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();\n        while (sc.hasNextInt()) {\n            list.add(sc.nextInt());\n        }\n        int[] height = new int[list.size()];\n        for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) height[i] = list.get(i);\n        System.out.println(solve(height));\n        sc.close();\n    }\n}",
        "javascript": "const fs = require('fs');\n\nfunction solve(height) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n    return 0;\n}\n\nconst input = fs.readFileSync(0, 'utf8').trim().split(/\\s+/);\nif (input.length > 0 && input[0] !== '') {\n    const height = input.map(Number);\n    console.log(solve(height));\n} else {\n    console.log(0);\n}",
        "c": "#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n\nint solve(int* height, int n) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n    return 0;\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int capacity = 1000;\n    int* height = (int*)malloc(capacity * sizeof(int));\n    int n = 0, val;\n    while (scanf(\"%d\", &val) == 1) {\n        if (n == capacity) {\n            capacity *= 2;\n            height = (int*)realloc(height, capacity * sizeof(int));\n        }\n        height[n++] = val;\n    }\n    printf(\"%d\\n\", solve(height, n));\n    free(height);\n    return 0;\n}"
